{{refimprove|date=July 2009}}
The '''National Schools Symphony Orchestra'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsso.org/|title=National Schools Symphony Orchestra|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref> – known for short as the '''NSSO''' – is a national orchestra in which the members are young people of secondary school age living in and around the [[United Kingdom]].
It was founded in 1995<ref>{{cite news|title=National Schools Symphony Orchestra |url=http://www.malverngazette.co.uk/news/local/9137593.National_Schools_Symphony_Orchestra/ |work=Malvern Gazette |date=14 July 2011 }}</ref> and has several distinguished patrons including [[Patrick Doyle]] and [[John Eliot Gardiner|Sir John Eliot Gardiner]].
==References== {{Reflist}}
==External links== https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-16317126
[[Category:British youth orchestras]] [[Category:1995 establishments in the United Kingdom]] [[Category:Arts organizations established in 1995]] [[Category:Musical groups established in 1995]] [[Category:Schools in the United Kingdom]]
{{UK-org-stub}}

{{Update|date=May 2018}}
{{primary sources|date=September 2012}}

'''RIBA International Awards''' are part of an awards program operated by the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], also encompassing the [[Stirling Prize]] and the [[RIBA European Award|European Award]].The RIBA International Award rewards "the excellent work being done by RIBA members around the world".<ref name="RIBA International Awards">{{citeweb|url=http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RIBAInternationalAwards/Home.aspx|title=RIBA International Awards|publisher=RIBA|accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref> They are awarded annually to a varying number of buildings. 

The shortlist for the [[Lubetkin Prize]] is made up of the winners of the RIBA International Awards.<ref>[http://www.architecture.com/Awards/LubetkinPrize/LubetkinPrize.aspx RIBA Lubetkin Prize website]</ref>

